Your current release YAML is hardcoded to SIT in the pipeline name, variable group, build-pipeline names, branch check, stage names, deploy environment, agent names, backup paths, and build tags, so I rewrote it around one `targetEnvironment` parameter and kept a single Manual Validation stage before deployment. That matches Azure Pipelines’ compile-time parameter/expression model and keeps your one-approval-only behavior.  ([Microsoft Learn][1])

I also changed the build-source validation from `refs/heads/sit` to `release/*` or `hotfix/*`, because your current file rejects any artifact not built from `sit`, which conflicts with the release-branch model we mapped. 

A few UAT/PROD values were not present in the file you shared, so I used the same naming pattern and marked the places you should verify, especially agent names and health-check URLs. 

